How Node.js Works
V8 JS Engine (C++)
* interprets JS -> binary

Non-Blocking
* does not wait for I/O ops
  - file ops
  - db calls
  - network calls
* events & callbacks used to synchronize I/O ops with
  "actors"

Single-Threaded
* uses event loop to perform non-blocking ops
* I/O operation -> 
  event loop continues -> 
  I/O operation returns -> 
  triggers callback -> 
  call back goes to event queue -> 
  event loop picks up callback

Common Node.js Uses
APIs
CLI tools
Real-time apps
Microservices
Web servers
Web scraping

NB: Node is NOT GOOD for CPU-intensive tasks

Setup
  package.json
	* first thing is almost always creating a package.json
	* you can do this with npm init
  	  - add the -y option to skip the interactivity
	* or just create it yourself from scratch
	* "scripts" - npm scripts you can use to 
	  - run tests,
 	  - start/stop your server

  entrypoint - index.js OR whatever name you specify
 	* just a script with statements
	* running script
		node <entrypoint>/<script-name.js>

  using a function in other files
  * you must export a function to be able to use it elsewhere
  * the native node.js module system is CommonJS

	in the script with the function you want to export
	-> module.exports = <function_name>;	

	in the script you want to use the function
	-> (const) myImportedFunction = require(<path_to_module_with_function>);

	this is called a default export;
	
	** to export multiple items:
	   in the exporting script
	   -> module.exports = { item1, item2, ... , itemN }

	   in the importing script
	   -> const { item1, item2, ... , itemN } = require(<path_to_module_with_function>);

  * using ES module system (import/export syntax)
	
	first change the module system in package.json
	- add the following key and value
	  -> "type": "module"

	in the script with the function you want to export
	-> export <function_name>() { ... } OR
           export default <function_name>

	in the script you want to use the function
	-> import myDefaultFunction from "<path_to_module_with_function>"; OR
	   import { function, function } from "<path_to_module_with_function>";
	
  * you can also export objects & other types of data in the same way


